1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,480
 So now we're going to do a real simple run-through

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:06,600
 of the kinds of things that you can do in HTML and forms.

3
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:08,840
 This is only the beginning and there's so many great

4
00:00:08,840 --> 00:00:13,180
 online resources for how to do forms in HTML.

5
00:00:13,180 --> 00:00:15,560
 So I've already showed you the basic text field.

6
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:17,900
 We'll talk about the password field, radio button,

7
00:00:17,900 --> 00:00:19,880
 checkbox, select and drop-down.

8
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:22,200
 And I just got kind of this one HTML page

9
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:25,320
 that you can view the source of and borrow.

10
00:00:25,320 --> 00:00:29,140
 I kind of write this stuff up for me for a quick reference.

11
00:00:29,140 --> 00:00:34,140
 So we've already talked about the text field, right?

12
00:00:34,140 --> 00:00:39,140
 So input type equals text and then the name is the value.

13
00:00:39,140 --> 00:00:41,400
 The ID, don't get too stuck on the ID.

14
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:45,000
 The ID has to do with how you associate the label tag

15
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,880
 with the field and so that that knows that somehow

16
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:50,440
 a count and this text box are connected.

17
00:00:50,440 --> 00:00:52,880
 So the ID is more of a browser thing

18
00:00:52,880 --> 00:00:56,640
 and the name equals is the thing that's gonna be sent

19
00:00:56,640 --> 00:00:57,480
 to the browser.

20
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:00,920
 So the browser's always gonna get key value pairs.

21
00:01:00,920 --> 00:01:03,160
 And so when we type beth and we hit submit,

22
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:04,800
 then we're gonna get the incoming post data

23
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:07,840
 is gonna have the value account equals beth.

24
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:10,160
 Now if you look at password, that's a type.

25
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:13,160
 Password for all intents and purposes is a text type.

26
00:01:13,160 --> 00:01:17,360
 And it shows it so people can't shoulder surf

27
00:01:17,360 --> 00:01:18,200
 and see what it is.

28
00:01:18,200 --> 00:01:20,200
 Of course they can watch you type your password,

29
00:01:20,200 --> 00:01:23,960
 but it shows asterisks in the box while you're typing.

30
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:26,360
 But then it's important to realize that once the data

31
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:30,080
 is submitted, the data is submitted in plain text.

32
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:34,240
 And so here's another one, another nickname.

33
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:38,320
 So nick equals N-I-C-K.

34
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:42,960
 So that's basically the variance of the input types of text.

35
00:01:42,960 --> 00:01:45,680
 Hidden, type equals hidden is another one

36
00:01:45,680 --> 00:01:47,460
 where you just don't see it in the user interface.

37
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:49,360
 We're gonna use one of those input type equals hidden

38
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:50,200
 in a bit.

39
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:54,560
 A radio button is designed for situations where there

40
00:01:54,560 --> 00:01:56,720
 you can only pick one of two things.

41
00:01:56,720 --> 00:01:58,620
 So when you hit A-M, the P-M goes off.

42
00:01:58,620 --> 00:02:00,240
 When you hit P-M, the A-M goes off.

43
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:02,180
 And you can actually have a whole bunch of them

44
00:02:02,180 --> 00:02:04,000
 and you can click them.

45
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,560
 Now they're drawn together because they're type equals radio

46
00:02:07,560 --> 00:02:08,880
 and then the name is identical.

47
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:10,960
 And interestingly, you can scatter these

48
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:12,080
 literally all over the page.

49
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:14,480
 It doesn't lead to very good user interface,

50
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:15,960
 but the way you go.

51
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:17,680
 And so what happens is, is again,

52
00:02:17,680 --> 00:02:20,620
 no matter how many of these you put with a name equals when,

53
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:22,460
 no matter where you put them on the page,

54
00:02:22,460 --> 00:02:25,520
 if you click one, all the others are gonna turn off.

55
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:27,040
 And so the one that's clicked,

56
00:02:27,040 --> 00:02:28,680
 they all have different values.

57
00:02:28,680 --> 00:02:30,920
 And so what'll happen is whatever one is clicked

58
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:33,420
 at the moment that you actually send it,

59
00:02:33,420 --> 00:02:37,640
 that will be the key value pair where when equals P-M,

60
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:39,600
 'cause only one can be selected,

61
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:41,680
 and it's up to you to make these things unique.

62
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:43,560
 Or you don't, maybe you don't want them unique.

63
00:02:43,560 --> 00:02:45,620
 You do whatever you want.

64
00:02:45,620 --> 00:02:48,500
 And so in this case, the P-M one is selected,

65
00:02:48,500 --> 00:02:52,700
 so we see when equals P-M in the incoming post data.

66
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:53,980
 So that's a radio button.

67
00:02:53,980 --> 00:02:57,060
 So this is a checkbox.

68
00:02:57,060 --> 00:03:01,820
 This is more, probably more useful in many ways.

69
00:03:01,820 --> 00:03:03,960
 Checkboxes, you can have as many that you want,

70
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:06,400
 and each of them are individual and distinct.

71
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:08,500
 So if you take a look, for example,

72
00:03:08,500 --> 00:03:11,520
 you see that you have different names,

73
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:14,480
 class one, class two, and class three, right?

74
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:19,480
 So that each checkbox has its own name,

75
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:22,520
 but the checkboxes are actually just little checkboxes.

76
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:23,960
 The text here is just text.

77
00:03:23,960 --> 00:03:26,520
 The text is not really a critical part of it.

78
00:03:26,520 --> 00:03:30,520
 The value, value is what will get sent

79
00:03:30,520 --> 00:03:31,880
 if that checkbox is checked.

80
00:03:31,880 --> 00:03:36,680
 And so in this example, we've checked pi-free and si-539,

81
00:03:36,680 --> 00:03:40,260
 and you'll notice that two of them have values,

82
00:03:40,260 --> 00:03:42,600
 and one of them doesn't.

83
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:44,560
 Now the key is often you're just checking

84
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:45,840
 to see if the data's there.

85
00:03:45,840 --> 00:03:50,080
 In this case, class three is not in the post data,

86
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:51,560
 and class one is on.

87
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:52,480
 That's the default.

88
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:56,200
 If you don't say value equals, it's like value equals on,

89
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:59,120
 or whatever the value is that you put in that checkbox.

90
00:03:59,120 --> 00:04:01,140
 And so you get to decide these.

91
00:04:01,140 --> 00:04:02,760
 You might easily think that you don't need

92
00:04:02,760 --> 00:04:05,240
 any values whatsoever, because you're really looking

93
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:06,900
 for the name of the field,

94
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:09,400
 and you want the name of the field to be distinct.

95
00:04:10,680 --> 00:04:13,080
 And so again, you can check as many of the checkboxes

96
00:04:13,080 --> 00:04:13,920
 as you want.

97
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:15,640
 You can uncheck 'em, you can check none of 'em,

98
00:04:15,640 --> 00:04:17,340
 and you can check all of 'em.

99
00:04:17,340 --> 00:04:18,640
 So those are checkboxes.

100
00:04:18,640 --> 00:04:20,160
 So to describe a drop-down,

101
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:23,720
 a drop-down is a multiple choice option, basically,

102
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:26,620
 for a single value that's gonna be sent back to you.

103
00:04:26,620 --> 00:04:32,000
 And so we have a select, which is the whole thing,

104
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,680
 and that gives the name the keyword

105
00:04:34,680 --> 00:04:36,480
 that it's gonna be sent back to.

106
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:38,320
 And then we have a series of options,

107
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:40,280
 and you'll notice there's no value on the select,

108
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:42,560
 but each option has its own value, right?

109
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:43,940
 So I happen to be going zero, one, two,

110
00:04:43,940 --> 00:04:45,720
 and these are strings, not numbers.

111
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:49,280
 They often are just numbers to make our lives simple.

112
00:04:49,280 --> 00:04:52,520
 And then you have some text, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

113
00:04:52,520 --> 00:04:55,460
 And so you pick one, in this case I leave it default,

114
00:04:55,460 --> 00:04:59,120
 and I hit the submit, so soda is gonna be equal to zero.

115
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:01,460
 So this happened to be the one that's selected

116
00:05:01,460 --> 00:05:03,720
 when we hit submit, okay?

117
00:05:03,720 --> 00:05:05,560
 So that's what a select looks like.

118
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:10,200
 You can also make a select that has some defaulted one,

119
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:12,640
 and so you just put selected on one of 'em.

120
00:05:12,640 --> 00:05:14,520
 So that means it's the dropdown.

121
00:05:14,520 --> 00:05:15,680
 They're all there, right?

122
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:16,520
 They're all there.

123
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:18,400
 If you click on this thing, you'll see,

124
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:19,600
 if you click on which snack,

125
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:21,820
 you're gonna see all the different snacks.

126
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:23,040
 Peanuts is preselected.

127
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:25,320
 And if I don't change it and hit submit,

128
00:05:25,320 --> 00:05:28,720
 then we're gonna see snack equals the value,

129
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:29,780
 which is peanuts.

130
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:32,260
 So that's an example that you don't have to make numbers,

131
00:05:32,260 --> 00:05:34,400
 although it's really common to be using numbers.

132
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:37,200
 So that's a dropdown with a default

133
00:05:37,200 --> 00:05:38,320
 other than the first item.

134
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:40,160
 The default is it's the first item

135
00:05:40,160 --> 00:05:42,540
 unless you do it otherwise.

136
00:05:42,540 --> 00:05:45,280
 When you're typing in comments or a blog post,

137
00:05:45,280 --> 00:05:48,920
 big long blob of text, you use a text area tag.

138
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:50,920
 The text area tag is a little bit different

139
00:05:50,920 --> 00:05:52,640
 in that it doesn't have a value equals.

140
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:54,360
 It does have a name equals.

141
00:05:54,360 --> 00:05:58,620
 It has rows and columns to tell how tall it is

142
00:05:58,620 --> 00:06:00,520
 and how wide it is.

143
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:02,780
 There are clever styling libraries

144
00:06:02,780 --> 00:06:05,280
 that make these a little prettier.

145
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:08,000
 But basically what it is, it's a series of text,

146
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,840
 including paragraphs, including new lines, et cetera.

147
00:06:10,840 --> 00:06:12,800
 And you're just allowed to type with new lines

148
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:14,400
 and edit and cursor around in here

149
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:16,200
 and build all kind of stuff.

150
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:20,320
 And then you send it in and you can put default text in here.

151
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:22,400
 You can edit the text, you can change it,

152
00:06:22,400 --> 00:06:24,280
 and it comes in as a key value pair

153
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:26,120
 with new lines and everything

154
00:06:26,120 --> 00:06:28,440
 and any weird spacing that you might put in.

155
00:06:28,440 --> 00:06:31,880
 But it's basically a block of text like a comment

156
00:06:31,880 --> 00:06:36,880
 or like a comment or a blog post or something like that.

157
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,360
 So the last thing on this page here is the submit button.

158
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:46,520
 And so you can make a type equals submit

159
00:06:46,520 --> 00:06:48,240
 and you can give it a name.

160
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:51,560
 And again, that's a key value pair and a value.

161
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:53,600
 Now, the submit is a little bit weird

162
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:57,680
 in that the value actually appears on the submit.

163
00:06:57,680 --> 00:07:01,020
 What we tend to do is the submit,

164
00:07:01,020 --> 00:07:02,920
 and if you were in a multi-language environment,

165
00:07:02,920 --> 00:07:06,440
 you're gonna want that to be whatever language of the user.

166
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:08,960
 So usually what we do is I name,

167
00:07:08,960 --> 00:07:13,960
 carefully name the variables or the name of the form,

168
00:07:13,960 --> 00:07:16,920
 and then I check for this to exist.

169
00:07:16,920 --> 00:07:20,640
 And if I have a bunch of buttons, I name them differently

170
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:22,860
 and don't really actually look at this text

171
00:07:22,860 --> 00:07:25,520
 because that text might wanna be translated

172
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:26,920
 at some point in time.

173
00:07:26,920 --> 00:07:28,920
 So that's an input type.

174
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:30,720
 Input type equals button.

175
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:34,280
 This is a little pattern where I'm gonna do like an escape

176
00:07:34,280 --> 00:07:38,120
 or a back or something like that.

177
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:41,080
 And then sometimes it's easier just to do

178
00:07:41,080 --> 00:07:43,760
 some little JavaScript and what this little JavaScript chunk

179
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:48,760
 is, location.hrf equals quote www.dj4e.com, return false.

180
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:53,700
 What this says is it actually sort of when you press

181
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:55,720
 this escape button, it goes up in the browser

182
00:07:55,720 --> 00:08:00,640
 and in effect pastes this little URL into the URL bar

183
00:08:00,640 --> 00:08:03,800
 and then hits enter and return false keeps the form

184
00:08:03,800 --> 00:08:04,960
 from being submitted.

185
00:08:04,960 --> 00:08:09,060
 And so this is a way that I often will put a simple cancel

186
00:08:09,060 --> 00:08:12,120
 or escape or something else in a form.

187
00:08:12,120 --> 00:08:15,720
 Just if I know the URL I want to go back to or go to,

188
00:08:15,720 --> 00:08:19,480
 then you can put it in here and unclick location.hrf.

189
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:23,720
 So those are the input types that have been around

190
00:08:23,720 --> 00:08:27,600
 for probably 20 years.

191
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:29,400
 Yeah, at least 20, 25 years.

192
00:08:29,400 --> 00:08:32,520
 HTML5 is a more recent phenomenon,

193
00:08:32,520 --> 00:08:35,080
 although by now it's pretty well supported

194
00:08:35,080 --> 00:08:39,160
 in most browsers, defined a whole new set of input types.

195
00:08:39,160 --> 00:08:41,240
 And what's nice about this is we were slowly

196
00:08:41,240 --> 00:08:43,040
 but surely building complex libraries

197
00:08:43,040 --> 00:08:44,560
 to solve all these problems.

198
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:46,200
 But now we can use these input types

199
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:48,920
 and now each browser can support them to their own way.

200
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:52,020
 And they all fall back to type equals text.

201
00:08:52,020 --> 00:08:54,320
 And so if you have a really old browser,

202
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:56,160
 these don't cause trouble.

203
00:08:56,160 --> 00:08:59,840
 So here's just some samples of some things.

204
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:03,760
 So type equals color is a color picker,

205
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:05,240
 and that's gonna pop up a color picker,

206
00:09:05,240 --> 00:09:06,520
 let you cruise around.

207
00:09:06,520 --> 00:09:09,280
 That color picker is defined by the browser

208
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:10,880
 and usually the operating system.

209
00:09:10,880 --> 00:09:12,360
 And so you'll pick a color.

210
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:16,680
 And then that color is going to go in in hex format.

211
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:19,880
 And that's the red, the green, and the blue.

212
00:09:19,880 --> 00:09:22,260
 And so that's what colors look like.

213
00:09:22,260 --> 00:09:25,440
 You can have type equals date.

214
00:09:25,440 --> 00:09:27,360
 And so here's a date and they pop in here.

215
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:28,920
 You're gonna pop up a date picker.

216
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:30,760
 For the birthday, you'll pop up a date picker

217
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:32,640
 and you'll be able to kind of move around

218
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:35,600
 and pick a date and then that'll put that date in

219
00:09:35,600 --> 00:09:36,520
 as a string.

220
00:09:36,520 --> 00:09:38,320
 They're all gonna turn into strings

221
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:39,680
 when they're being sent in.

222
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:44,600
 A couple of the other ones like email, name equals email.

223
00:09:44,600 --> 00:09:46,520
 That basically does validation that says

224
00:09:46,520 --> 00:09:47,960
 it's gotta have an at sign.

225
00:09:47,960 --> 00:09:50,800
 There's some rules about what is and isn't a valid email.

226
00:09:50,800 --> 00:09:53,820
 And so this will refuse to submit this form

227
00:09:53,820 --> 00:09:56,920
 unless there's a valid email in there.

228
00:09:56,920 --> 00:09:58,840
 The same is true for number.

229
00:09:58,840 --> 00:10:02,240
 You, if you put something that's like 25

230
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:05,640
 and it's not between one and five with min and max here,

231
00:10:05,640 --> 00:10:07,880
 is we're gonna refuse to submit the form.

232
00:10:07,880 --> 00:10:10,440
 The same is true for a type equals URL.

233
00:10:10,440 --> 00:10:13,000
 It's really a validation on the form to say look,

234
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,080
 you can't put something in here that's not a valid URL.

235
00:10:16,080 --> 00:10:20,080
 And just to prove that it doesn't matter,

236
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:23,320
 if you make any type, which flying doesn't exist,

237
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:25,920
 you can type something in and it just functions

238
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:26,760
 as a text field.

239
00:10:26,760 --> 00:10:29,960
 And so in a way all these fall back to text fields.

240
00:10:29,960 --> 00:10:33,340
 Now the key thing is is when you hit the submit button,

241
00:10:33,340 --> 00:10:35,880
 normally that gathers up the form

242
00:10:35,880 --> 00:10:37,380
 and sends it to the server.

243
00:10:37,380 --> 00:10:40,080
 But when you use this HTML5 validation

244
00:10:40,080 --> 00:10:42,800
 like date, number, email, URL,

245
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:44,900
 it actually will before it,

246
00:10:44,900 --> 00:10:47,560
 before it you hit the submit button,

247
00:10:47,560 --> 00:10:48,920
 before it actually sends it,

248
00:10:48,920 --> 00:10:52,120
 it's gonna do a quick validation on these things.

249
00:10:52,120 --> 00:10:54,320
 And it will actually stop and say you know what,

250
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:55,640
 you didn't get that one right.

251
00:10:55,640 --> 00:10:57,040
 And it just refuses to submit.

252
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:59,440
 So you can't override that in your application.

253
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:02,840
 What happens is is the data doesn't get submitted at all

254
00:11:02,840 --> 00:11:06,200
 until, so the browser blocks the submission of the data.

255
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:08,580
 Now if it's not an HTML5 browser,

256
00:11:08,580 --> 00:11:11,320
 it's gonna get submitted with no validation whatsoever.

257
00:11:11,320 --> 00:11:14,160
 So we still have to kind of check this data for sanity,

258
00:11:14,160 --> 00:11:16,760
 which we'll talk about soon about how to do that.

259
00:11:16,760 --> 00:11:18,400
 In the server, but this is quite nice

260
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:21,120
 because it gives your user some immediate feedback,

261
00:11:21,120 --> 00:11:22,560
 kind of customized to the browser,

262
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:24,880
 so the browser takes some responsibility

263
00:11:24,880 --> 00:11:27,480
 for helping get the user to type the right stuff in.

264
00:11:27,480 --> 00:11:32,920
 And so that is a romp through HTML forms.

